- **AoS (Array of Structs)**: Good when working with entire object.
- **SoA (Struct of Arrays)**: Better for SIMD/parallelism, cache efficiency.

Example:
```cpp
// AoS
struct Particle {float x,y,z;};
Particle p[N];

// SoA
struct Particles {float x[N], y[N], z[N];};
```

Cache locality directly impacts performance.

- **pImpl (pointer to implementation)** hides private details in a separate struct.
- Header only exposes a forward declaration, source file contains details.

Benefits:
- Reduces compile-time dependencies.
- Improves binary compatibility.
- Encapsulation.

```cpp
class Foo {
  struct Impl;
  std::unique_ptr<Impl> p;
};
```

- Use **templates + std::function + type erasure**.
- Or use `std::variant` to store event types.

```cpp
struct EventA {...};
struct EventB {...};

using Event = std::variant<EventA, EventB>;
```

Dispatch with `std::visit` instead of `dynamic_cast`.
